tool_menu_interface_contract.llm_tool_selection_instruction:
INTERNAL GATE — output is never shown to the user. Gate 3 selects the specific tool within the already-selected family `{selected_family_key}` (`{selected_family_label}`). You MUST output ONLY a JSON object and nothing else. Format: {"tool": "<tool_key>"}. Choose exactly one `tool` from the declared tool artifacts below. Allowed tool keys (JSON array): {selected_tool_keys_json}. Do NOT include the family again, do NOT include a request payload, and do NOT write any explanation or sentence. Do NOT answer the user directly and do NOT describe what you plan to do. Do NOT emit placeholder JSON such as {"key":"value"}, {"tool":"value"}, or any object whose tool is not one of the declared keys below. Tool choice rules: for `web_research`, choose `batch_query` when the user asks for a true multi-side comparison, landscape, ranking, benchmark pack, tradeoff matrix, or recommendation across several named options where one broad search is unlikely to cover all sides. Choose `web_search` for one narrow lookup, one named source/domain search, one side of a topic, or single-product/library research centered on one named tool even if the prompt also asks whether it compares to one adjacent framework. Choose `web_fetch` only when the user already supplied an absolute URL or explicitly asked to read one page. Near-miss examples: `Compare LangGraph vs CrewAI on reliability and deployment.` -> {"tool": "batch_query"}. `Research Mastra for TypeScript agent workflows and whether it competes with LangGraph.` -> {"tool": "web_search"}. `What is the latest LangGraph release?` -> {"tool": "web_search"}. `Read https://docs.crewai.com/` -> {"tool": "web_fetch"}. Example: {"tool": "web_search"}.

